The two Poles
The European Parliament has recently condemned the attempt by the Polish government to strip Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
Former leader of Solidarity, former political prisoner and former foreign minister - he led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign yet another declaration stating that he was not an agent of the secret police during the communist era.
European parliamentarians have spoken of a "witch hunt" regarding the behavior of the Polish government, and Geremek stated that the lustration law [decommunization] constitutes a threat to public freedoms.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and of inciting anti-Polish sentiment.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A decision by the constitutional court dated May 11 largely invalidated the lustration law, allowing Geremek to retain his seat in the European Parliament, at least for now.
But this law is part of a general policy of the Polish government whose only aim is to weaken the country's institutions and democratic fabric.
What is happening in Poland, the country where the collapse of communism began?
Every revolution passes through two phases: first a struggle for freedom, then a fight for power.
The first is an emancipation of the human soul by which man expresses the best within him, while the second unleashes the worst: envy, intrigues, greed, suspicion, and the desire for revenge.
The revolution sparked by the Polish trade union Solidarity followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced underground when martial law was declared in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reemerge in the open in 1989, in the wake of the "perestroika" initiated by Gorbachev.
During the negotiations that ended the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached a compromise that paved the way for the peaceful dismantling of the communist dictatorship throughout the Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a compromising attitude rather than one of revenge, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a country divided between all-powerful winners and oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes in government, but the country has remained stable. The former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and the market economy.
But not everyone followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity revenge-seekers, post-communist provincial agitators, xenophobic and antisemitic groups, heirs to pre-war chauvinism, and circles surrounding Radio Maryja, the mouthpiece of ethno-clerical fundamentalism.
Alarming signs are visible everywhere: the authority of the judiciary is being undermined, the independence of the Constitutional Court is being called into question, officials are being bought off, and the role of the prosecutor is being politicized.
Every day, social life is subjected to repressive regulation.
Why all this?
Every successful revolution has its winners and losers.
The Polish revolution brought public freedoms, but also more crime, the market economy but also the risk of business failure and high unemployment, as well as the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by an income gap that is widening.
It opened Poland to Europe, but it also induced fear of the foreign and fear of a mass Western cultural invasion.
For the losers of the 1989 Polish revolution, freedom comes with a lot of uncertainties.
In large companies, Solidarity workers have become victims of the freedoms they have won.
In the communist prison universe, people were considered to belong to the State, but the latter took care of them.
In a world of freedom, there is no one to take care of us.
It is within this atmosphere of anxiety that the ruling coalition governs, combining the conservative potion of George Bush with the centralism of Vladimir Putin.
Solidarity veterans thought the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the firmament.
But the guilty among the communists were not punished and the virtuous Solidarity activists were not rewarded.
Also, the sense of injustice has given rise to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed both against former enemies and old friends who seemed to be coming out on top.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was Poland's greatest success in 300 years.
For them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland was in need of a moral revolution that would ensure crimes would not go unpunished, virtue would be rewarded, and injustices would be redressed.
After their victory in the 2005 general elections, the political parties of the losers chose a method: a large purge.
According to initial estimates, the lustration process should take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the archives of the security services; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people targeted by the lustration must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be dismissed and prohibited from practicing their profession for ten years.
