Cardinal Dziwisz of Cracovie reminds us that there is no place "for revenge, vengeance, disrespect for human dignity, and unfounded accusations".
Never since the fall of communism has a cardinal used such strong words.
Should this lustration have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The aim of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, and not a hunt for suspects, proven or not, of having belonged to the secret police.
If this hunt had been organized in 1990, neither Leszek Balcerowicz's economic reforms nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would be a member of neither NATO nor the European Union.
Today, two Polands are facing each other.
Poland of suspicion, fear, and vengeance fights Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland - one of openness and tolerance, that of John Paul II and Czeslaw Milisz, of my friends from the underground and from prison - must prevail.
I believe that the Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The decision of the constitutional court leaves hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will not destroy either what gave it birth, the will for freedom, or what it has generated, a democratic state.
